nd": 777}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000080242"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "8-oxo-dG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988555908203125, "span": {"begin": 787, "end": 795}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "replication forks", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6862844824790955, "span": {"begin": 918, "end": 935}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:105376906", "100862688", "100616102"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "repair polymerases", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9420064091682434, "span": {"begin": 937, "end": 955}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:353497"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Human Y-family DNA polymerases", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963341355323792, "span": {"begin": 1017, "end": 1047}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9770547151565552, "span": {"begin": 1017, "end": 1022}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51455"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Rev 1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926813840866089, "span": {"begin": 1049, "end": 1054}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51426"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pol &kappa;, &iota;, and &eta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9930669665336609, "span": {"begin": 1056, "end": 1086}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3981"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "DNA repair polymerases", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9908431172370911, "span": {"begin": 1092, "end": 1114}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2521"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TLS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.49840861558914185, "span": {"begin": 1178, "end": 1181}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:105376906", "100862688", "100616102"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "repair polymerase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7821357250213623, "span": {"begin": 1237, "end": 1254}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51426"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pol &kappa; and &eta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9853984117507935, "span": {"begin": 1286, "end": 1307}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000080242"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "8-oxo-dG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991033673286438, "span": {"begin": 1327, "end": 1335}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:61404"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dATP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990874528884888, "span": {"begin": 1353, "end": 1357}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:20794"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "G", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.5158253312110901, "span": {"begin": 1390, "end": 1391}}], "text": "Mutagenicity of oxidative DNA lesions has been extensively studied; incorrect base insertion opposite unrepaired oxidative DNA lesions during replication is a well-established event.  For example, 8-oxo-dG and FaPydG, the two most prominent oxidative DNA lesions, are able to form base pairs with dATP, giving rise to G:C&rarr;T:A transversions with subsequent DNA synthesis ADDIN RW.CITE{{317 Gehrke,T. 2013; 319 Freudenthal,B. 2013; 318 Markkanen,E. 2017}}(Gehrke et al., 2013; Freudenthal et al., 2013; Markkanen, 2017). Replicative DNA polymerases such as DNA polymerase &alpha;, &delta;, and &epsilon; (pol &alpha;, &delta;, &epsilon;) have a poor ability to extend the DNA strand past 8-oxo-dG:dCTP base pairs and may cause replication to stall or incorrectly insert dATP opposite 8-oxo-dG ADDIN RW.CITE{{320 Hashimoto,K. 2004; 321 Markkanen,E. 2012}}(Hashimoto et al., 2004; Markkanen et al., 2012). In stalled replication forks, repair polymerases may be recruited to perform translesion DNA synthesis (TLS). Human Y-family DNA polymerases (Rev 1, pol &kappa;, &iota;, and &eta;) are DNA repair polymerases mainly involved in TLS for stalled replication forks. However, TLS is not free of error and its accuracy differs for each repair polymerase. For example, it is known that pol &kappa; and &eta; perform TLS across 8-oxo-dG and often insert dATP opposite the lesion, generating G:C&rarr;T:A transversions. The error-prone nature of bypassing unrepaired oxidative lesions has been described in many previous studies and reviews ADDIN RW.CITE{{322 Greenberg,M. 2012; 243 Maddukuri,L. 2014; 323 Taggart,D. 2014; 324 Sha,Y. 2017}}(Greenberg, 2012; Maddukuri et al., 2014; Taggart et al., 2014; Sha et al., 2017).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:20:15 +0000 2026"}